data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

EF Core 11 **removes the sync-over-async opt-in** for the Cosmos DB provider entirely. Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — the opt-in configuration is no longer honored.

The Cosmos DB SDK is async-only, and EF Core previously shimmed sync calls by blocking on async internally. That shim is gone in EF Core 11.

## The fix

Convert all synchronous calls to their async counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

This will ripple up the call stack — callers must also become `async`/`await` all the way to the controller actions (which ASP.NET Core already supports natively).
